    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid, or more accurately, lactate, is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration when your muscles are working harder than the oxygen supply can keep up with the demand. It's produced when glucose is broken down without sufficient oxygen in the muscle cells. To get rid of it, your body uses several mechanisms, including converting lactate back into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy or transported to other tissues like the liver for recycling. Your body is quite efficient at managing this metabolic byproduct, though the buildup is what causes that familiar burning sensation during intense exercise.",
